import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
from sklearn.decomposition import PCA
import numpy as np
import seaborn as sns
from scipy.stats import anderson
import warnings
from sklearn.preprocessing import MinMaxScaler, StandardScaler, PowerTransformer, RobustScaler
from scipy.stats.mstats import winsorize
from sklearn.utils import resample
import os
# specify path to the dataset
file_path = r"C:\Users\USER\Desktop\credit_card_fraud_detection\creditcard.csv"
# load dataset into a data frame; df
df = pd.read_csv(file_path)
# display few rows of the data frame to confirm it's loaded correctly
print(df.head( ))
# Load your DataFrame (assuming it is named 'df')
# Example: df = pd.read_csv('your_data.csv')

# Extract the principal components into a separate DataFrame
pcs = df[[f'V{i}' for i in range(1, 29)]]  # Use uppercase 'V' for the columns

# Initialize PCA and fit it to the principal components
pca = PCA()
pca.fit(pcs)

# Explained variance for each principal component
explained_variance = pca.explained_variance_ratio_

# Calculate cumulative explained variance
cumulative_variance = explained_variance.cumsum()

# Plotting the Scree Plot and Cumulative Explained Variance
plt.figure(figsize=(8, 4))

# Scree Plot
plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
plt.bar(range(1, len(explained_variance) + 1), explained_variance, alpha=0.7)
plt.xlabel('Principal Components')
plt.ylabel('Explained Variance Ratio')
plt.title('Scree Plot')

# Cumulative Explained Variance Plot
plt.subplot(1, 2, 2)
plt.plot(range(1, len(cumulative_variance) + 1), cumulative_variance, marker='o', linestyle='--')
plt.axhline(y=0.90, color='r', linestyle='--', label='90% Variance')
plt.xlabel('Principal Components')
plt.ylabel('Cumulative Explained Variance')
plt.title('Cumulative Explained Variance')
plt.xticks(range(1, len(cumulative_variance) + 1))
plt.legend()
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Determine the number of PCs to retain for 90% variance
threshold = 0.90
num_pcs_to_keep = (cumulative_variance >= threshold).argmax() + 1  # +1 for index
print(f'Number of PCs to keep for {threshold*100}% variance: {num_pcs_to_keep}')

# Examine stats of Time column
# Examine Time column for presence of outliers
# Examine skewness and kurtosis of Time column
# Examine distribution of Time column using Anderson Darling test.
# Visualize Time column using box plot and histogram.
import pandas as pd
import numpy as np
from scipy import stats
from scipy.stats import anderson
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import seaborn as sns

# Summary statistics for 'Time' column
time_stats = df['Time'].describe()
skewness = df['Time'].skew()
kurtosis = df['Time'].kurtosis()

print("Statistics for 'Time' column:")
print(time_stats)
print(f"\nSkewness of 'Time': {skewness}")
print(f"Kurtosis of 'Time': {kurtosis}")

# Calculate Q1 (25th percentile) and Q3 (75th percentile)
Q1 = df['Time'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df['Time'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

# Determine outlier boundaries
lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

# Identify outliers
outliers = df[(df['Time'] < lower_bound) | (df['Time'] > upper_bound)]

# Calculate the number and percentage of outliers
number_outliers = len(outliers)
percentage_outliers = (len(outliers) / len(df)) * 100

# Print number and percentage of outliers
print(f"\nNumber of Outliers: {len(outliers)}")
print(f"Percentage of Outliers: {percentage_outliers:.2f}%")


# Anderson-Darling Test for Normality
ad_result = anderson(df['Time'], dist='norm')
print("\nAnderson-Darling Test Result for 'Time':")
print(f"Test Statistic: {ad_result.statistic}")

# Loop through significance levels and compare with test statistic
normality = True
for i, critical_value in enumerate(ad_result.critical_values):
    sig_level = ad_result.significance_level[i]
    print(f"Significance level: {sig_level}%, Critical value: {critical_value}")
    if ad_result.statistic > critical_value:
        print(f"At {sig_level}% significance level, the 'Time' column does NOT follow a normal distribution.")
        normality = False
        break

if normality:
    print("\nBased on the Anderson-Darling test, the 'Time' column follows a normal distribution.")
else:
    print("\nThe 'Time' column does NOT follow a normal distribution based on the Anderson-Darling test.")

# Set up side-by-side plots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(8, 4))

# Boxplot for 'Time' column
sns.boxplot(x=df['Time'], ax=axes[0])
axes[0].set_title("Boxplot of 'Time'")

# Histogram for 'Time' column
sns.histplot(df['Time'], kde=True, ax=axes[1])
axes[1].set_title("Histogram of 'Time'")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Apply winzorization method to V1 column to handle the remaining outliers after yeo-johnson,s trans.
from scipy.stats.mstats import winsorize

# Define the limits for Winsorization (e.g., 5% from both ends)
# This means values below the 5th percentile and above the 95th percentile will be capped.
limits = [0.05, 0.05]

# Apply Winsorization on the V1 column and overwrite it with the Winsorized values
df['V1'] = winsorize(df['V1'], limits=limits).data 
#df['V1'] = winsorize(df['V1'], limits=limits)

skewness = df['V1'].skew()
kurtosis = df['V1'].kurtosis()

print("Statistics for 'V1' column after winzorization:")
print(time_stats)
print(f"\nSkewness of 'V1'after winzorization: {skewness}")
print(f"Kurtosis of 'V1' after winzorization: {kurtosis}")

# Calculate Q1 (25th percentile) and Q3 (75th percentile)
Q1 = df['V1'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df['V1'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

# Determine outlier boundaries
lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

# Identify outliers
outliers = df[(df['V1'] < lower_bound) | (df['V1'] > upper_bound)]

# Calculate the number and percentage of outliers
number_outliers = len(outliers)
percentage_outliers = (len(outliers) / len(df)) * 100

# Print number and percentage of outliers
print(f"\nNumber of Outliers after winzorization: {len(outliers)}")
print(f"Percentage of Outliers after winzorization: {percentage_outliers:.2f}%")

print("\nAnderson-Darling Test Result for 'V1' after winzorization:")
print(f"Test Statistic after yeo-johnson trans.: {ad_result.statistic}")

# Loop through significance levels and compare with test statistic
normality = True
for i, critical_value in enumerate(ad_result.critical_values):
    sig_level = ad_result.significance_level[i]
    print(f"Significance level: {sig_level}%, Critical value: {critical_value}")
    if ad_result.statistic > critical_value:
        print(f"At {sig_level}% significance level, the 'V1' column does NOT follow a normal distribution.")
        normality = False
        break

# Transform V12 column using yoe-johnson transformation since it has negative values
from sklearn.preprocessing import PowerTransformer

# Step 1: Create an instance of the PowerTransformer with Yeo-Johnson method
transformer = PowerTransformer(method='yeo-johnson')

# Step 2: Fit and transform the V11 column, and overwrite it with the transformed values
df['V12'] = transformer.fit_transform(df[['V12']])

# Summary statistics for 'V10' column
time_stats = df['V12'].describe()
skewness = df['V12'].skew()
kurtosis = df['V12'].kurtosis()

print("Statistics for 'V12' column after yeo-johnson trans.:")
print(time_stats)
print(f"\nSkewness of 'V12'after yeo-johnson trans. : {skewness}")
print(f"Kurtosis of 'V12' after yeo-johnson trans. : {kurtosis}")

# Calculate Q1 (25th percentile) and Q3 (75th percentile)
Q1 = df['V12'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df['V12'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

# Determine outlier boundaries
lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

# Identify outliers
outliers = df[(df['V12'] < lower_bound) | (df['V12'] > upper_bound)]

# Calculate the number and percentage of outliers
number_outliers = len(outliers)
percentage_outliers = (len(outliers) / len(df)) * 100

# Print number and percentage of outliers
print(f"\nNumber of Outliers after yeo-johnson trans.: {len(outliers)}")
print(f"Percentage of Outliers after yeo-johnson trans.: {percentage_outliers:.2f}%")


# Anderson-Darling Test for Normality
ad_result = anderson(df['V12'], dist='norm')
print("\nAnderson-Darling Test Result for 'V12' after yeo-johnson trans.:")
print(f"Test Statistic after yeo-johnson trans.: {ad_result.statistic}")

# Loop through significance levels and compare with test statistic
normality = True
for i, critical_value in enumerate(ad_result.critical_values):
    sig_level = ad_result.significance_level[i]
    print(f"Significance level: {sig_level}%, Critical value: {critical_value}")
    if ad_result.statistic > critical_value:
        print(f"At {sig_level}% significance level, the 'V12' column does NOT follow a normal distribution.")
        normality = False
        break

if normality:
    print("\nBased on the Anderson-Darling test, the 'V12' column follows a normal distribution.")
else:
    print("\nThe 'V12' column does NOT follow a normal distribution based on the Anderson-Darling test.")

fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(8, 4))

# Boxplot for 'V12' column

axes[0].set_title("Boxplot of 'V12' after yeo-johnson trans.")

axes[1].set_title("Histogram of 'V12' after yeo-johnson trans.")

# This means values below the 5th percentile and above the 95th percentile will be capped.
limits = [0.05, 0.05]

# Apply Winsorization on the V18 column and overwrite it with the Winsorized values
df['V18'] = winsorize(df['V18'], limits=limits).data 
#df['V18'] = winsorize(df['V18'], limits=limits)

# Summary statistics for 'V18' column
time_stats = df['V18'].describe()
skewness = df['V18'].skew()
kurtosis = df['V18'].kurtosis()

print("Statistics for 'V18' column after winzorization:")
print(time_stats)
print(f"\nSkewness of 'V18'after winzorization: {skewness}")
print(f"Kurtosis of 'V18' after winzorization: {kurtosis}")

# Calculate Q1 (25th percentile) and Q3 (75th percentile)
Q1 = df['V18'].quantile(0.25)
Q3 = df['V18'].quantile(0.75)
IQR = Q3 - Q1

# Determine outlier boundaries
lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

# Identify outliers
outliers = df[(df['V18'] < lower_bound) | (df['V18'] > upper_bound)]

# Calculate the number and percentage of outliers
number_outliers = len(outliers)
percentage_outliers = (len(outliers) / len(df)) * 100

# Print number and percentage of outliers
print(f"\nNumber of Outliers after winzorization: {len(outliers)}")
print(f"Percentage of Outliers after winzorization: {percentage_outliers:.2f}%")


# Anderson-Darling Test for Normality
ad_result = anderson(df['V18'], dist='norm')
print("\nAnderson-Darling Test Result for 'V18' after winzorization:")
print(f"Test Statistic after yeo-johnson trans.: {ad_result.statistic}")

# Loop through significance levels and compare with test statistic
normality = True
for i, critical_value in enumerate(ad_result.critical_values):
    sig_level = ad_result.significance_level[i]
    print(f"Significance level: {sig_level}%, Critical value: {critical_value}")
    if ad_result.statistic > critical_value:
        print(f"At {sig_level}% significance level, the 'V18' column does NOT follow a normal distribution.")
        normality = False
        break

if normality:
    print("\nBased on the Anderson-Darling test, the 'V18' column follows a normal distribution.")
else:
    print("\nThe 'V18' column does NOT follow a normal distribution based on the Anderson-Darling test.")

# Set up side-by-side plots
fig, axes = plt.subplots(1, 2, figsize=(8, 4))

# Boxplot for 'V17' column
sns.boxplot(x=df['V18'], ax=axes[0])
axes[0].set_title("Boxplot of 'V18' after winzorization")

# Histogram for 'Time' column
sns.histplot(df['V18'], kde=True, ax=axes[1])
axes[1].set_title("Histogram of 'V18' after winzorization")

plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()

# Up sample Class column

# Step 1: Separate the majority and minority classes
df_majority = df[df['Class'] == 0]  # Replace 0 with the majority class label
df_minority = df[df['Class'] == 1]  # Replace 1 with the minority class label

# Step 2: Upsample the minority class
df_minority_upsampled = resample(df_minority, 
                                  replace=True,        # Sample with replacement
                                  n_samples=len(df_majority),  # To match majority class
                                  random_state=42)    # Reproducible results

# Step 3: Combine the majority class with the upsampled minority class
df_upsampled = pd.concat([df_majority, df_minority_upsampled])

# Step 4: Shuffle the combined dataset
df_upsampled = df_upsampled.sample(frac=1, random_state=42).reset_index(drop=True)

# Check the class distribution after upsampling
print("\nClass distribution after upsampling:")
print(df_upsampled['Class'].value_counts())

# Step 5: Visualize the class distribution with a histogram
